## Acknowledgments

This work emerged from questioning why multiplication doesn't "make things bigger" when multiplying by 1, and from observing that binary addition creates dimensional states (the 0 in 1+1=10₂) that traditional interpretation collapses. We acknowledge the intuition that "everything has two sides" as the philosophical seed of this mathematical framework.

Special recognition goes to the fundamental observation that in binary computing—the very foundation of digital reality—the operation 1 + 1 = 10 creates a zero in position 0 that persists when adding subsequent values. This dimensional persistence in the computational substrate that powers modern civilization suggests that persistent mathematics may be more fundamental than the collapsed mathematics we teach in schools.

